TY  - JOUR
T1  - Employment Discrimination: An Organizational Model
AU  - Haberfeld, Yitchak
Y1  - 1992/03/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256476
DO  - 10.5465/256476
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 161
EP  - 180
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Empirical findings have indicated that gender-based discrimination is manifested during the assignment of workers to organizational positions. Since the position occupied has a major effect on a worker's salary, discriminatory processes in assigning positions should be incorporated into a salary discrimination model. Organizational variables were more important than individual variables in explaining both legitimate salary differentials between the men and women studied and gender-based salary discrimination.
AB  - Empirical findings have indicated that gender-based discrimination is manifested during the assignment of workers to organizational positions. Since the position occupied has a major effect on a worker's salary, discriminatory processes in assigning positions should be incorporated into a salary discrimination model. Organizational variables were more important than individual variables in explaining both legitimate salary differentials between the men and women studied and gender-based salary discrimination.
