TY  - JOUR
T1  - Outcomes of Federal Court Decisions on Sexual Harassment
AU  - Terpstra, David E.
AU  - Baker, Douglas D.
Y1  - 1992/03/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256477
DO  - 10.5465/256477
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 181
EP  - 190
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examined the influence of nine case characteristics on the outcomes of federal court cases involving sexual harassment. Case characteristics that were related to the courts' decisions were the severity of the behavior involved, the presence of witnesses and documents, whether complainants had notified their companies of the harassment before filing charges, and whether the organizations had taken action. We compared findings to the results of a previous study involving harassment charges filed with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
AB  - This study examined the influence of nine case characteristics on the outcomes of federal court cases involving sexual harassment. Case characteristics that were related to the courts' decisions were the severity of the behavior involved, the presence of witnesses and documents, whether complainants had notified their companies of the harassment before filing charges, and whether the organizations had taken action. We compared findings to the results of a previous study involving harassment charges filed with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
